      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Scientists Say Slower Atlantic Currents Could Mean a Colder Europe'' (news article, Dec. 1) succinctly explains complicated phenomena.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Scientists Say Slower Atlantic Currents Could Mean a Colder Europe'' (news article, Dec. 1) succinctly explains complicated phenomena.</p>
        <p>So the circulatory system of the biosphere that supports us all may indeed be beginning to slow down, as predicted by climate-change computer models.</p>
        <p>Since even minor current fluctuations have major weather effects, this should give us pause.</p>
        <p>Actually, any news related to global warming should be leading the world's major newspapers and broadcasts, for complex science combined with long-term thinking highlights what is actually a simple ethical truth: No other issue is as important as the possibility, whether remote or likely, that we could make our only planet unlivable.</p>
        <p>Dan Carsen  Brookline, Mass., Dec. 1, 2005</p>
      </block>
